# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kruskal-mst
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In computer science, a **disjoint-set data structure**, also called a **union–find data structure** or **merge–find set**, is a data structure that stores a collection of disjoint (non-overlapping) sets.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Equivalently, it stores a partition of a set into disjoint subsets.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] It provides operations for adding new sets, merging sets (replacing them with their union), and finding a representative member of a set.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The last operation makes it possible to determine efficiently whether any two elements belong to the same set or to different sets.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] While there are several ways of implementing disjoint-set data structures, in practice they are often identified with a particular implementation known as a **disjoint-set forest**.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This specialized type of forest performs union and find operations in near-constant amortized time.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] For a sequence of m addition, union, or find operations on a disjoint-set forest with n nodes, the total time required is *O*(*m*α(*n*)), where α(*n*) is the extremely slow-growing inverse Ackermann function.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Although disjoint-set forests do not guarantee this time per operation, each operation rebalances the structure (via tree compression) so that subsequent operations become faster.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] As a result, disjoint-set forests are both asymptotically optimal and practically efficient.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures play a key role in Kruskal's algorithm for finding the minimum spanning tree of a graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The importance of minimum spanning trees means that disjoint-set data structures support a wide variety of algorithms.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In addition, these data structures find applications in symbolic computation and in compilers, especially for register allocation problems.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set forests were first described by Bernard A.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1973, their time complexity was bounded to $O(\log ^{*}(n))$ , the iterated logarithm of n , by Hopcroft and Ullman.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1975, Robert Tarjan was the first to prove the $O(m\alpha (n))$ (inverse Ackermann function) upper bound on the algorithm's time complexity.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1979, he showed that this was the lower bound for a certain class of algorithms, pointer algorithms, that include the Galler-Fischer structure.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1989, Fredman and Saks showed that $\Omega (\alpha (n))$ (amortized) words of $O(\log n)$ bits must be accessed by *any* disjoint-set data structure per operation, thereby proving the optimality of the data structure in this model.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1991, Galil and Italiano published a survey of data structures for disjoint-sets.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Anderson and Heather Woll described a parallelized version of Union–Find that never needs to block.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 2007, Sylvain Conchon and Jean-Christophe Filliâtre developed a semi-persistent version of the disjoint-set forest data structure and formalized its correctness using the proof assistant Rocq (then: *Coq*).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] "Semi-persistent" means that previous versions of the structure are efficiently retained, but accessing previous versions of the data structure invalidates later ones.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Their fastest implementation achieves performance almost as efficient as the non-persistent algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] They do not perform a complexity analysis.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Variants of disjoint-set data structures with better performance on a restricted class of problems have also been considered.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Gabow and Tarjan showed that if the possible unions are restricted in certain ways, then a truly linear time algorithm is possible.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In particular, linear time is achievable if a "union tree" is given a priori.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is a tree that includes all elements of the sets.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Let p[*v*] denote the parent in the tree, then the assumption is that union operations must have the form **union**(*v*,p[*v*]) for some *v*.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this and the following section we describe the most common implementation of the disjoint-set data structure, as a forest of parent pointer trees.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This representation is known as **Galler-Fischer trees**.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Each node in a disjoint-set forest consists of a pointer and some auxiliary information, either a size or a rank (but not both).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The pointers are used to make parent pointer trees, where each node that is not the root of a tree points to its parent.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] To distinguish root nodes from others, their parent pointers have invalid values, such as a circular reference to the node or a sentinel value.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Each tree represents a set stored in the forest, with the members of the set being the nodes in the tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Root nodes provide set representatives: Two nodes are in the same set if and only if the roots of the trees containing the nodes are equal.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Nodes in the forest can be stored in any way convenient to the application, but a common technique is to store them in an array.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this case, parents can be indicated by their array index.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Every array entry requires Θ(log *n*) bits of storage for the parent pointer.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] A comparable or lesser amount of storage is required for the rest of the entry, so the number of bits required to store the forest is Θ(*n* log *n*).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] If an implementation uses fixed size nodes (thereby limiting the maximum size of the forest that can be stored), then the necessary storage is linear in n.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures support three operations: Making a new set containing a new element; Finding the representative of the set containing a given element; and Merging two sets.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The `MakeSet` operation adds a new element into a new set containing only the new element, and the new set is added to the data structure.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the data structure is instead viewed as a partition of a set, then the `MakeSet` operation enlarges the set by adding the new element, and it extends the existing partition by putting the new element into a new subset containing only the new element.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In a disjoint-set forest, `MakeSet` initializes the node's parent pointer and the node's size or rank.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This operation has linear time complexity.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In particular, initializing a disjoint-set forest with n nodes requires *O*(*n*) time.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lack of a parent assigned to the node implies that the node is not present in the forest.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In practice, `MakeSet` must be preceded by an operation that allocates memory to hold x.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] As long as memory allocation is an amortized constant-time operation, as it is for a good dynamic array implementation, it does not change the asymptotic performance of the random-set forest.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The `Find` operation follows the chain of parent pointers from a specified query node x until it reaches a root element.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This root element represents the set to which x belongs and may be x itself.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] `Find` returns the root element it reaches.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Performing a `Find` operation presents an important opportunity for improving the forest.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The time in a `Find` operation is spent chasing parent pointers, so a flatter tree leads to faster `Find` operations.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] When a `Find` is executed, there is no faster way to reach the root than by following each parent pointer in succession.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] However, the parent pointers visited during this search can be updated to point closer to the root.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Because every element visited on the way to a root is part of the same set, this does not change the sets stored in the forest.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] But it makes future `Find` operations faster, not only for the nodes between the query node and the root, but also for their descendants.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This updating is an important part of the disjoint-set forest's amortized performance guarantee.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] There are several algorithms for `Find` that achieve the asymptotically optimal time complexity.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] One family of algorithms, known as **path compression**, makes every node between the query node and the root point to the root.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This implementation makes two passes, one up the tree and one back down.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] It requires enough scratch memory to store the path from the query node to the root (in the above pseudocode, the path is implicitly represented using the call stack).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This can be decreased to a constant amount of memory by performing both passes in the same direction.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Tarjan and Van Leeuwen also developed one-pass `Find` algorithms that retain the same worst-case complexity but are more efficient in practice.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] These are called path splitting and path halving.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both of these update the parent pointers of nodes on the path between the query node and the root.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The operation `Union(*x*, *y*)` replaces the set containing x and the set containing y with their union.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] `Union` first uses `Find` to determine the roots of the trees containing x and y.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the roots are the same, there is nothing more to do.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Otherwise, the two trees must be merged.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is done by either setting the parent pointer of x's root to y's, or setting the parent pointer of y's root to x's.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The choice of which node becomes the parent has consequences for the complexity of future operations on the tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] If it is done carelessly, trees can become excessively tall.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] For example, suppose that `Union` always made the tree containing x a subtree of the tree containing y.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The resulting forest contains a single tree whose root is n, and the path from 1 to n passes through every node in the tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] For this forest, the time to run `Find(1)` is *O*(*n*).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In an efficient implementation, tree height is controlled using **union by size** or **union by rank**.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both of these require a node to store information besides just its parent pointer.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This information is used to decide which root becomes the new parent.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Both strategies ensure that trees do not become too deep.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In the case of union by size, a node stores its size, which is simply its number of descendants (including the node itself).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] When the trees with roots x and y are merged, the node with more descendants becomes the parent.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the two nodes have the same number of descendants, then either one can become the parent.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In both cases, the size of the new parent node is set to its new total number of descendants.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The number of bits necessary to store the size is clearly the number of bits necessary to store n.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This adds a constant factor to the forest's required storage.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] For union by rank, a node stores its *rank*, which is an upper bound for its height.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] When a node is initialized, its rank is set to zero.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] To merge trees with roots x and y, first compare their ranks.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the ranks are different, then the larger rank tree becomes the parent, and the ranks of x and y do not change.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] If the ranks are the same, then either one can become the parent, but the new parent's rank is incremented by one.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] While the rank of a node is clearly related to its height, storing ranks is more efficient than storing heights.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The height of a node can change during a `Find` operation, so storing ranks avoids the extra effort of keeping the height correct.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] It can be shown that every node has rank $\lfloor \log n\rfloor$ or less.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Consequently, each rank can be stored in *O*(log log *n*) bits and all the ranks can be stored in *O*(*n* log log *n*) bits.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes the ranks an asymptotically negligible portion of the forest's size.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is clear from the above implementations that the size and rank of a node do not matter unless a node is the root of a tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Once a node becomes a child, its size and rank are never accessed again.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] There is a variant of the `Union` operation in which the user determines the representative of the formed set.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is not hard to add this functionality to the above algorithms without losing efficiency.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] A disjoint-set forest implementation in which `Find` does not update parent pointers, and in which `Union` does not attempt to control tree heights, can have trees with height *O*(*n*).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In such a situation, the `Find` and `Union` operations require *O*(*n*) time.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] If an implementation uses path compression alone, then a sequence of n `MakeSet` operations, followed by up to *n* − 1 `Union` operations and *f* `Find` operations, has a worst-case running time of $\Theta (n+f\cdot \left(1+\log _{2+f/n}n\right))$ .
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Using union by rank, but without updating parent pointers during `Find`, gives a running time of $\Theta (m\log n)$ for m operations of any type, up to n of which are `MakeSet` operations.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The combination of path compression, splitting, or halving, with union by size or by rank, reduces the running time for m operations of any type, up to n of which are `MakeSet` operations, to $\Theta (m\alpha (n))$ .
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes the amortized running time of each operation $\Theta (\alpha (n))$ .
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This is asymptotically optimal, meaning that every disjoint set data structure must use $\Omega (\alpha (n))$ amortized time per operation.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Here, the function $\alpha (n)$ is the inverse Ackermann function.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The inverse Ackermann function grows extraordinarily slowly, so this factor is 4 or less for any n that can actually be written in the physical universe.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This makes disjoint-set operations practically amortized constant time.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The precise analysis of the performance of a disjoint-set forest is somewhat intricate.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] However, there is a much simpler analysis that proves that the amortized time for any m `Find` or `Union` operations on a disjoint-set forest containing n objects is *O*(*m* log* *n*), where log* denotes the iterated logarithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lemma 1: As the find function follows the path along to the root, the rank of node it encounters is increasing.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] We claim that as Find and Union operations are applied to the data set, this fact remains true over time.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Initially when each node is the root of its own tree, it's trivially true.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The only case when the rank of a node might be changed is when the Union by Rank operation is applied.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this case, a tree with smaller rank will be attached to a tree with greater rank, rather than vice versa.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] And during the find operation, all nodes visited along the path will be attached to the root, which has larger rank than its children, so this operation won't change this fact either.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Lemma 2: A node u which is root of a subtree with rank r has at least $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Assume that a node u with rank r has at least 2*r* nodes.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Then when two trees with rank r are merged using the operation Union by Rank, a tree with rank *r* + 1 results, the root of which has at least $2^{r}+2^{r}=2^{r+1}$ nodes.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] From lemma 2, we know that a node u which is root of a subtree with rank r has at least $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] We will get the maximum number of nodes of rank r when each node with rank r is the root of a tree that has exactly $2^{r}$ nodes.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] At any particular point in the execution, we can group the vertices of the graph into "buckets", according to their rank.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] We define the buckets' ranges inductively, as follows: Bucket 0 contains vertices of rank 0.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Bucket 2 contains vertices of ranks 2 and 3.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Then bucket B will have vertices with ranks in the interval $[{\text{tower}}(B-1),{\text{tower}}(B)-1]$ .
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] We can make two observations about the buckets' sizes.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The maximum number of elements in bucket $\left[B,2^{B}-1\right]$ is at most ${\frac {2n}{2^{B}}}$ .
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Since each find operation makes exactly one traversal that leads to a root, we have *T*1 = *O*(*m*).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Also, from the bound above on the number of buckets, we have *T*2 = *O*(*m*log**n*).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] For T3, suppose we are traversing an edge from u to v, where u and v have rank in the bucket [*B*, 2*B* − 1] and v is not the root (at the time of this traversing, otherwise the traversal would be accounted for in T1).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Fix u and consider the sequence $v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{k}$ that take the role of v in different find operations.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Because of path compression and not accounting for the edge to a root, this sequence contains only different nodes and because of Lemma 1 we know that the ranks of the nodes in this sequence are strictly increasing.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The worst-case time of the `Find` operation in trees with **Union by rank** or **Union by weight** is $\Theta (\log n)$ (i.e., it is $O(\log n)$ and this bound is tight).
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Blum gave an implementation of the operations that does not use path compression, but compresses trees during $union$ .
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] His implementation runs in $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ time per operation, and thus in comparison with Galler and Fischer's structure it has a better worst-case time per operation, but inferior amortized time.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In 1999, Alstrup et al. gave a structure that has optimal worst-case time $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ together with inverse-Ackermann amortized time.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The regular implementation as disjoint-set forests does not react favorably to the deletion of elements, in the sense that the time for `Find` will not improve as a result of the decrease in the number of elements.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is possible to extend certain disjoint-set forest structures to allow backtracking.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The basic form of backtracking is to allow a `Backtrack(1)` operation, that undoes the last `Union`.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] A more advanced form allows `Backtrack(i)`, which undoes the last i unions.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The following complexity result is known: there is a data structure which supports `Union` and `Find` in $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ time per operation, and `Backtrack` in $O(1)$ time.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] In this result, the freedom of `Union` to choose the representative of the formed set is essential.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Better amortized time cannot be achieved within the class of separable pointer algorithms.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Disjoint-set data structures model the partitioning of a set, for example to keep track of the connected components of an undirected graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This model can then be used to determine whether two vertices belong to the same component, or whether adding an edge between them would result in a cycle.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The Union–Find algorithm is used in high-performance implementations of unification.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] This data structure is used by the Boost Graph Library to implement its Incremental Connected Components functionality.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] It is also a key component in implementing Kruskal's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] The Hoshen-Kopelman algorithm uses a Union-Find.
[src:kruskal-mst/disjoint-set-data-structure] Union-find can be used to implement reasonably performant Type inference algorithms.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] A **greedy algorithm** is an algorithm which, at each step, makes the choice that is locally optimal, and subsequently does not reconsider past choices.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Greedy algorithms are often used to solve combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] If an optimization problem only depends on the partial solution of solving it for one subproblem, we can solve this problem by "greedily" considering only the locally optimal subproblem.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] In this sense, a greedy algorithm is a special case of a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] In many cases, a greedy algorithm does not produce an exact solution, but can yield solutions that approximate an exact solution in a reasonable amount of time.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] An example of a problem which admits an exact greedy solution, the activity selection problem.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Given a collection of tasks which can be done between allotted time intervals, the problem is to determine the maximum number of tasks that can be done.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] A greedy algorithm in $O(n\log(n))$ which solves this problem sorts the tasks by the end time and then repeatedly chooses the first task that begins after the last task ended.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Many classic algorithms in computer science such as the Huffman coding algorithm, Prim's algorithm, Kruskal's algorithm, and Dijkstra's algorithm all use greedy properties in their design.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Mathematicians frequently use *greedy strategies* in proofs as well.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] A classic example is what Raphael Yuster refers to as the greedy proof that every tournament in graph contains a Hamiltonian path.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Since there is no formal definition of what a greedy algorithm is, a complete characterization of when a problem admits a greedy algorithm as a solution is not known.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] However, special cases have been identified.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Jack Edmonds showed that a greedy algorithm can be used to solve a class of linear combinatorial optimization problems with a matroid structure.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Later Bernhard Korte and László Lovász characterized a broader class of optimization problems by introducing the notion of a greedoid.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] This allowed, for example, a proof of the optimality of Prim's algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Algorithms which undo past steps are not greedy.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] For example, the Gale-Shapley algorithm is not a greedy algorithm since although it constructs a solution by choosing the current best pairing, in the process, existing solutions may be modified.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] One technique used to prove the optimiality of greedy algorithms is an exchange argument.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] The exchange argument demonstrates that any solution different from the greedy solution is at most as good as the greedy solution.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Conclude by induction that the greedy solution is optimal.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Starting from A, a greedy algorithm that tries to find the maximum by following the greatest slope will find the local maximum at "m", oblivious to the global maximum at "M".
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] To reach the largest sum, at each step, the greedy algorithm will choose what appears to be the optimal immediate choice, so it will choose 12 instead of 3 at the second step, and will not reach the best solution, which contains 99.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Graph theory is a rich source of greedy algorithms.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Computing scientists frequently use greedy algorithms frequently to compute graph invariants.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Greedy algorithms are also used to find upper bounds for the chromatic numbers.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] A simple example is the bound $\chi (G)\leq \Delta (G)+1$ obtained by a greedy algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] We begin by taking a vertex that has not been colored.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Since it has at most $\Delta (G)$ neighbours, at most $\Delta (G)$ colors are used in adjacent vertices, leaving a color free for the vertex under consideration.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] A solution to the NP-complete travelling salesman problem can be approximated by starting from an empty edge set and then adding the next cheapest edge which is a subgraph of a complete tour.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] This greedy algorithm has been proven to yield at most $\Theta (\log n)$ times longer than the optimal tour.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Another example is that a solution for the 0-1 knapsack problem can be approximated by using the greedy algorithm for the fractional knapsack problem.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] This greedy algorithm has been proven to yield a solution at least half the value of the optimal solution.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Solutions for submodular maximization are approximated using a greedy algorithm which yields a solution at least half the value of the optimal solution.
[src:kruskal-mst/greedy-algorithm] Problems for which greedy algorithms are used to provide approximation algorithms include the set cover, load balancing, Steiner tree and independent set problem.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] A minimum spanning tree of a connected weighted graph is a connected subgraph, without cycles, for which the sum of the weights of all the edges in the subgraph is minimal.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] For a disconnected graph, a minimum spanning forest is composed of a minimum spanning tree for each connected component.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] This algorithm was first published by Joseph Kruskal in 1956, and was rediscovered soon afterward by Loberman & Weinberger (1957).
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Other algorithms for this problem include Prim's algorithm, Borůvka's algorithm, and the reverse-delete algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] At the termination of the algorithm, the forest forms a minimum spanning forest of the graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] If the graph is connected, the forest has a single component and forms a minimum spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] The following code is implemented with a disjoint-set data structure.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] It represents the forest *F* as a set of undirected edges, and uses the disjoint-set data structure to efficiently determine whether two vertices are part of the same tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] For a graph with E edges and V vertices, Kruskal's algorithm can be shown to run in time *O*(*E* log *E*) time, with simple data structures.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] This time bound is often written instead as *O*(*E* log *V*), which is equivalent for graphs with no isolated vertices, because for these graphs *V* / 2 ≤ *E* < *V*2 and the logarithms of V and V2 are again within a constant factor of each other.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] To achieve this bound, first sort the edges by weight using a comparison sort in *O*(*E* log *E*) time.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Once sorted, it is possible to loop through the edges in sorted order in constant time per edge.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Next, use a disjoint-set data structure, with a set of vertices for each component, to keep track of which vertices are in which components.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Creating this structure, with a separate set for each vertex, takes V operations and *O*(*V*) time.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] The final iteration through all edges performs two find operations and possibly one union operation per edge.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] These operations take amortized time *O*(*α*(*V*)) time per operation, giving worst-case total time *O*(*E* *α*(*V*)) for this loop, where α is the extremely slowly growing inverse Ackermann function.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] This part of the time bound is much smaller than the time for the sorting step, so the total time for the algorithm can be simplified to the time for the sorting step.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] First, it is proved that the algorithm produces a spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Second, it is proved that the constructed spanning tree is of minimal weight.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Let G be a connected, weighted graph and let Y be the subgraph of G produced by the algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Y cannot have a cycle, as by definition an edge is not added if it results in a cycle.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Y cannot be disconnected, since the first encountered edge that joins two components of Y would have been added by the algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] We show that the following proposition ***P*** is true by induction: If *F* is the set of edges chosen at any stage of the algorithm, then there is some minimum spanning tree that contains *F* and none of the edges rejected by the algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Kruskal's algorithm is inherently sequential and hard to parallelize.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] It is, however, possible to perform the initial sorting of the edges in parallel or, alternatively, to use a parallel implementation of a binary heap to extract the minimum-weight edge in every iteration.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] As parallel sorting is possible in time $O(n)$ on $O(\log n)$ processors, the runtime of Kruskal's algorithm can be reduced to *O*(*E* α(*V*)), where α again is the inverse of the single-valued Ackermann function.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] A variant of Kruskal's algorithm, named Filter-Kruskal, has been described by Osipov et al. and is better suited for parallelization.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] The basic idea behind Filter-Kruskal is to partition the edges in a similar way to quicksort and filter out edges that connect vertices of the same tree to reduce the cost of sorting.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] The following pseudocode demonstrates this.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Filter-Kruskal lends itself better to parallelization as sorting, filtering, and partitioning can easily be performed in parallel by distributing the edges between the processors.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Finally, other variants of a parallel implementation of Kruskal's algorithm have been explored.
[src:kruskal-mst/kruskal-s-algorithm] Examples include a scheme that uses helper threads to remove edges that are definitely not part of the MST in the background, and a variant which runs the sequential algorithm on *p* subgraphs, then merges those subgraphs until only one, the final MST, remains.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A **minimum spanning tree** (**MST**) or **minimum weight spanning tree** is a subset of the edges of a connected, edge-weighted undirected graph that connects all the vertices together, without any cycles and with the minimum possible total edge weight.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] That is, it is a spanning tree whose sum of edge weights is as small as possible.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] More generally, any edge-weighted undirected graph (not necessarily connected) has a **minimum spanning forest**, which is a union of the minimum spanning trees for its connected components.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] There are many use cases for minimum spanning trees.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] One example is a telecommunications company trying to lay cable in a new neighborhood.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If it is constrained to bury the cable only along certain paths (e.g. roads), then there would be a graph containing the points (e.g. houses) connected by those paths.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Some of the paths might be more expensive, because they are longer, or require the cable to be buried deeper; these paths would be represented by edges with larger weights.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Currency is an acceptable unit for edge weight – there is no requirement for edge lengths to obey normal rules of geometry such as the triangle inequality.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A *spanning tree* for that graph would be a subset of those paths that has no cycles but still connects every house; there might be several spanning trees possible.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A *minimum spanning tree* would be one with the lowest total cost, representing the least expensive path for laying the cable.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If there are n vertices in the graph, then each spanning tree has *n* − 1 edges.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] There may be several minimum spanning trees of the same weight; in particular, if all the edge weights of a given graph are the same, then every spanning tree of that graph is minimum.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Since A and B differ despite containing the same nodes, there is at least one edge that belongs to one but not the other.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Among such edges, let *e*1 be the one with least weight; this choice is unique because the edge weights are all distinct.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Without loss of generality, assume *e*1 is in A.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] As B is an MST, {*e*1} ∪ *B* must contain a cycle C with *e*1.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] As a tree, A contains no cycles, therefore C must have an edge *e*2 that is not in A.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Since *e*1 was chosen as the unique lowest-weight edge among those belonging to exactly one of A and B, the weight of *e*2 must be greater than the weight of *e*1.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] As *e*1 and *e*2 are part of the cycle C, replacing *e*2 with *e*1 in B therefore yields a spanning tree with a smaller weight.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] This contradicts the assumption that B is an MST.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] More generally, if the edge weights are not all distinct then only the (multi-)set of weights in minimum spanning trees is certain to be unique; it is the same for all minimum spanning trees.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If the weights are *positive*, then a minimum spanning tree is, in fact, a minimum-cost subgraph connecting all vertices, since if a subgraph contains a cycle, removing any edge along that cycle will decrease its cost and preserve connectivity.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: Assume the contrary, i.e. that e belongs to an MST *T*1.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Then deleting e will break *T*1 into two subtrees with the two ends of e in different subtrees.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The remainder of C reconnects the subtrees, hence there is an edge f of C with ends in different subtrees, i.e., it reconnects the subtrees into a tree *T*2 with weight less than that of *T*1, because the weight of f is less than the weight of e.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: Assume that there is an MST T that does not contain e.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Adding e to T will produce a cycle, that crosses the cut once at e and crosses back at another edge e'.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Deleting e' we get a spanning tree *T*∖{*e'*} ∪ {*e*} of strictly smaller weight than T.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] This contradicts the assumption that T was a MST.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] By a similar argument, if more than one edge is of minimum weight across a cut, then each such edge is contained in some minimum spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: if e was not included in the MST, removing any of the (larger cost) edges in the cycle formed after adding e to the MST, would yield a spanning tree of smaller weight.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If T is a tree of MST edges, then we can *contract* T into a single vertex while maintaining the invariant that the MST of the contracted graph plus T gives the MST for the graph before contraction.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In all of the algorithms below, m is the number of edges in the graph and n is the number of vertices.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The first algorithm for finding a minimum spanning tree was developed by Czech scientist Otakar Borůvka in 1926 (see Borůvka's algorithm).
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Its purpose was an efficient electrical coverage of Moravia.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The algorithm proceeds in a sequence of stages.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In each stage, called *Boruvka step*, it identifies a forest F consisting of the minimum-weight edge incident to each vertex in the graph G, then forms the graph *G*1 = *G* \ *F* as the input to the next step.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Here *G* \ *F* denotes the graph derived from G by contracting edges in F (by the Cut property, these edges belong to the MST).
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Since the number of vertices is reduced by at least half in each step, Boruvka's algorithm takes *O*(*m* log *n*) time.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A second algorithm is Prim's algorithm, which was invented by Vojtěch Jarník in 1930 and rediscovered by Prim in 1957 and Dijkstra in 1959.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Basically, it grows the MST (T) one edge at a time.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Initially, T contains an arbitrary vertex.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In each step, T is augmented with a least-weight edge (*x*,*y*) such that x is in T and y is not yet in T.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] By the Cut property, all edges added to T are in the MST.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Its run-time is either *O*(*m* log *n*) or *O*(*m* + *n* log *n*), depending on the data-structures used.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A third algorithm commonly in use is Kruskal's algorithm, which also takes *O*(*m* log *n*) time.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A fourth algorithm, not as commonly used, is the reverse-delete algorithm, which is the reverse of Kruskal's algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Its runtime is O(*m* log *n* (log log *n*)3).
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] All four of these are greedy algorithms.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Since they run in polynomial time, the problem of finding such trees is in **FP**, and related decision problems such as determining whether a particular edge is in the MST or determining if the minimum total weight exceeds a certain value are in **P**.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Several researchers have tried to find more computationally-efficient algorithms.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In a comparison model, in which the only allowed operations on edge weights are pairwise comparisons, Karger, Klein & Tarjan (1995) found a linear time randomized algorithm based on a combination of Borůvka's algorithm and the reverse-delete algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The fastest non-randomized comparison-based algorithm with known complexity, by Bernard Chazelle, is based on the soft heap, an approximate priority queue.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Its running time is *O*(*m* α(*m*,*n*)), where α is the classical functional inverse of the Ackermann function.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The function α grows extremely slowly, so that for all practical purposes it may be considered a constant no greater than 4; thus Chazelle's algorithm takes very close to linear time.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] *m*/*n* ≥ log log log *n*), then a deterministic algorithm by Fredman and Tarjan finds the MST in time O(*m*).
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The algorithm executes a number of phases.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Each phase executes Prim's algorithm many times, each for a limited number of steps.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The run-time of each phase is O(*m* + *n*).
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If the number of vertices before a phase is n', the number of vertices remaining after a phase is at most ${\tfrac {n'}{2^{m/n'}}}$ .
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Hence, at most log**n* phases are needed, which gives a linear run-time for dense graphs.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] There are other algorithms that work in linear time on dense graphs.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If the edge weights are integers represented in binary, then deterministic algorithms are known that solve the problem in *O*(*m* + *n*) integer operations.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Whether the problem can be solved *deterministically* for a *general graph* in *linear time* by a comparison-based algorithm remains an open question.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Deterministic algorithms are known that solve the problem for planar graphs in linear time.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] By the Euler characteristic of planar graphs, *m* ≤ 3*n* - 6 ∈ *O*(*n*), so this is in time *O*(*n*).
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Given graph G where the nodes and edges are fixed but the weights are unknown, it is possible to construct a binary decision tree (DT) for calculating the MST for any permutation of weights.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Each internal node of the DT contains a comparison between two edges, e.g.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] "Is the weight of the edge between x and y larger than the weight of the edge between w and z?".
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The two children of the node correspond to the two possible answers "yes" or "no".
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In each leaf of the DT, there is a list of edges from G that correspond to an MST.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime complexity of a DT is the largest number of queries required to find the MST, which is just the depth of the DT.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A DT for a graph G is called *optimal* if it has the smallest depth of all correct DTs for G.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] For every integer r, it is possible to find optimal decision trees for all graphs on r vertices by brute-force search.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Seth Pettie and Vijaya Ramachandran have found a provably optimal deterministic comparison-based minimum spanning tree algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The following is a simplified description of the algorithm.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Partition the graph to components with at most r vertices in each component.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] This partition uses a soft heap, which "corrupts" a small number of the edges of the graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Use the optimal decision trees to find an MST for the uncorrupted subgraph within each component.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Add back the corrupted edges to the resulting forest to form a subgraph guaranteed to contain the minimum spanning tree, and smaller by a constant factor than the starting graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Apply the optimal algorithm recursively to this graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime of all steps in the algorithm is *O*(*m*), *except for the step of using the decision trees*.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime of this step is unknown, but it has been proved that it is optimal - no algorithm can do better than the optimal decision tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Thus, this algorithm has the peculiar property that it is *provably optimal* although its runtime complexity is *unknown*.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Research has also considered parallel algorithms for the minimum spanning tree problem.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] With a linear number of processors it is possible to solve the problem in *O*(log *n*) time.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The problem can also be approached in a distributed manner.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If each node is considered a computer and no node knows anything except its own connected links, one can still calculate the distributed minimum spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Frieze and Steele also proved convergence in probability.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Svante Janson proved a central limit theorem for weight of the MST.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] For uniform random weights in $[0,1]$ , the exact expected size of the minimum spanning tree has been computed for small complete graphs.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] There is a fractional variant of the MST, in which each edge is allowed to appear "fractionally".
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Formally, a **fractional spanning set** of a graph (V,E) is a nonnegative function *f* on *E* such that, for every non-trivial subset *W* of *V* (i.e., *W* is neither empty nor equal to *V*), the sum of *f*(*e*) over all edges connecting a node of *W* with a node of *V*\*W* is at least 1.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Intuitively, *f*(*e*) represents the fraction of e that is contained in the spanning set.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A **minimum fractional spanning set** is a fractional spanning set for which the sum $\sum _{e\in E}f(e)\cdot w(e)$ is as small as possible.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If the fractions *f*(*e*) are forced to be in {0,1}, then the set *T* of edges with f(e)=1 are a spanning set, as every node or subset of nodes is connected to the rest of the graph by at least one edge of *T*.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Moreover, if *f* minimizes $\sum _{e\in E}f(e)\cdot w(e)$ , then the resulting spanning set is necessarily a tree, since if it contained a cycle, then an edge could be removed without affecting the spanning condition.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The fractional MST problem can be solved in polynomial time using the ellipsoid method.
[src:kruskal-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Minimum spanning trees have direct applications in the design of networks, including computer networks, telecommunications networks, transportation networks, water supply networks, and electrical grids (which they were first invented for, as mentioned above).
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] The **reverse-delete algorithm** is an algorithm in graph theory used to obtain a minimum spanning tree from a given connected, edge-weighted graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] It first appeared in Kruskal (1956), but it should not be confused with Kruskal's algorithm which appears in the same paper.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] If the graph is disconnected, this algorithm will find a minimum spanning tree for each disconnected part of the graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] The set of these minimum spanning trees is called a minimum spanning forest, which contains every vertex in the graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] This algorithm is a greedy algorithm, choosing the best choice given any situation.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] It is the reverse of Kruskal's algorithm, which is another greedy algorithm to find a minimum spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] Kruskal’s algorithm starts with an empty graph and adds edges while the Reverse-Delete algorithm starts with the original graph and deletes edges from it.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] In the above the graph is the set of edges *E* with each edge containing a weight and connected vertices *v1* and *v2*.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] In the following example green edges are being evaluated by the algorithm and red edges have been deleted.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] The algorithm can be shown to run in *O*(*E* log *V* (log log *V*)3) time (using big-O notation), where *E* is the number of edges and *V* is the number of vertices.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] It is recommended to read the proof of the Kruskal's algorithm first.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] First, it is proved that the edges that remain after the algorithm is applied form a spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] Second, it is proved that the spanning tree is of minimal weight.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] The remaining sub-graph (g) produced by the algorithm is not disconnected since the algorithm checks for that in line 7.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] The result sub-graph cannot contain a cycle since if it does then when moving along the edges we would encounter the max edge in the cycle and we would delete that edge.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] Thus g must be a spanning tree of the main graph G.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] We show that the following proposition ***P*** is true by induction: If F is the set of edges remained at the end of the while loop, then there is some minimum spanning tree that (its edges) are a subset of *F*.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] Now assume ***P*** is true for some non-final edge set *F* and let *T* be a minimum spanning tree that is contained in *F.*we must show that after deleting edge e in the algorithm there exists some (possibly other) spanning tree T' that is a subset of F.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] 2. otherwise, if e belongs to T: first note that the algorithm only removes the edges that do not cause a disconnectedness in the F. so e does not cause a disconnectedness.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] But deleting e causes a disconnectedness in tree T (since it is a member of T). assume e separates T into sub-graphs t1 and t2.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] 4. secondly we prove T' is a ***minimum*** spanning tree . we have three cases for the edges "e" and " f ". wt is the weight function.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] 3. so wt(f) = wt(e) so T' is also a ***minimum*** spanning tree. so again ***P***holds.
[src:kruskal-mst/reverse-delete-algorithm] 3. so ***P***holds when the while loop is done ( which is when we have seen all the edges ) and we proved at the end F becomes a ***spanning tree*** and we know F has a ***minimum*** spanning tree as its subset . so F must be the ***minimum spanning tree*** itself .
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In the mathematical field of graph theory, a **spanning tree** *T* of an undirected graph *G* is a subgraph that is a tree which includes all of the vertices of *G*.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In general, a graph may have several spanning trees, but a graph that is not connected will not contain a spanning tree (see about spanning forests below).
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] If all of the edges of *G* are also edges of a spanning tree *T* of *G*, then *G* is a tree and is identical to *T* (that is, a tree has a unique spanning tree and it is itself).
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Several pathfinding algorithms, including Dijkstra's algorithm and the A* search algorithm, internally build a spanning tree as an intermediate step in solving the problem.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In order to minimize the cost of power networks, wiring connections, piping, automatic speech recognition, etc., people often use algorithms that gradually build a spanning tree (or many such trees) as intermediate steps in the process of finding the minimum spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The Internet and many other telecommunications networks have transmission links that connect nodes together in a mesh topology that includes some loops.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In order to avoid bridge loops and routing loops, many routing protocols designed for such networks—including the Spanning Tree Protocol, Open Shortest Path First, Link-state routing protocol, Augmented tree-based routing, etc.—require each router to remember a spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A special kind of spanning tree, the Xuong tree, is used in topological graph theory to find graph embeddings with maximum genus.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A Xuong tree is a spanning tree such that, in the remaining graph, the number of connected components with an odd number of edges is as small as possible.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A Xuong tree and an associated maximum-genus embedding can be found in polynomial time.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A tree is a connected undirected graph with no cycles.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] It is a spanning tree of a graph *G* if it spans *G* (that is, it includes every vertex of *G*) and is a subgraph of *G* (every edge in the tree belongs to *G*).
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A spanning tree of a connected graph *G* can also be defined as a maximal set of edges of *G* that contains no cycle, or as a minimal set of edges that connect all vertices.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Adding just one edge to a spanning tree will create a cycle; such a cycle is called a **fundamental cycle** with respect to that tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] There is a distinct fundamental cycle for each edge not in the spanning tree; thus, there is a one-to-one correspondence between fundamental cycles and edges not in the spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] For any given spanning tree the set of all *E* − *V* + 1 fundamental cycles forms a cycle basis, i.e., a basis for the cycle space.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Dual to the notion of a fundamental cycle is the notion of a **fundamental cutset** with respect to a given spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] By deleting just one edge of the spanning tree, the vertices are partitioned into two disjoint sets.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The fundamental cutset is defined as the set of edges that must be removed from the graph *G* to accomplish the same partition.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Thus, each spanning tree defines a set of *V* − 1 fundamental cutsets, one for each edge of the spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A collection of disjoint (unconnected) trees is described as a *forest*.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A *spanning forest* in a graph is a subgraph that is a forest with an additional requirement.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] There are two incompatible requirements in use, of which one is relatively rare.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The number *t*(*G*) of spanning trees of a connected graph is a well-studied invariant.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] More generally, for any graph *G*, the number *t*(*G*) can be calculated in polynomial time as the determinant of a matrix derived from the graph, using Kirchhoff's matrix-tree theorem.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Specifically, to compute *t*(*G*), one constructs the Laplacian matrix of the graph, a square matrix in which the rows and columns are both indexed by the vertices of *G*.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The resulting matrix is singular, so its determinant is zero.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] However, deleting the row and column for an arbitrarily chosen vertex leads to a smaller matrix whose determinant is exactly *t*(*G*).
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The term *t*(*G* − *e*) in this formula counts the spanning trees of *G* that do not use edge *e*, and the term *t*(*G*/*e*) counts the spanning trees of *G* that use *e*.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In this formula, if the given graph *G* is a multigraph, or if a contraction causes two vertices to be connected to each other by multiple edges, then the redundant edges should not be removed, as that would lead to the wrong total.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] For instance a bond graph connecting two vertices by *k* edges has *k* different spanning trees, each consisting of a single one of these edges.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The Tutte polynomial of a graph can be defined as a sum, over the spanning trees of the graph, of terms computed from the "internal activity" and "external activity" of the tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Its value at the arguments (1,1) is the number of spanning trees or, in a disconnected graph, the number of maximal spanning forests.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The Tutte polynomial can also be computed using a deletion-contraction recurrence, but its computational complexity is high: for many values of its arguments, computing it exactly is #P-complete, and it is also hard to approximate with a guaranteed approximation ratio.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The point (1,1), at which it can be evaluated using Kirchhoff's theorem, is one of the few exceptions.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A single spanning tree of a graph can be found in linear time by either depth-first search or breadth-first search.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Both of these algorithms explore the given graph, starting from an arbitrary vertex *v*, by looping through the neighbors of the vertices they discover and adding each unexplored neighbor to a data structure to be explored later.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] They differ in whether this data structure is a stack (in the case of depth-first search) or a queue (in the case of breadth-first search).
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In either case, one can form a spanning tree by connecting each vertex, other than the root vertex *v*, to the vertex from which it was discovered.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] This tree is known as a depth-first search tree or a breadth-first search tree according to the graph exploration algorithm used to construct it.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Depth-first search trees are a special case of a class of spanning trees called Trémaux trees, named after the 19th-century discoverer of depth-first search.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Spanning trees are important in parallel and distributed computing, as a way of maintaining communications between a set of processors; see for instance the Spanning Tree Protocol used by OSI link layer devices or the Shout (protocol) for distributed computing.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] However, the depth-first and breadth-first methods for constructing spanning trees on sequential computers are not well suited for parallel and distributed computers.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Instead, researchers have devised several more specialized algorithms for finding spanning trees in these models of computation.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In certain fields of graph theory it is often useful to find a minimum spanning tree of a weighted graph.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Optimal spanning tree problems have also been studied for finite sets of points in a geometric space such as the Euclidean plane.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] For such an input, a spanning tree is again a tree that has as its vertices the given points.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The quality of the tree is measured in the same way as in a graph, using the Euclidean distance between pairs of points as the weight for each edge.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Thus, for instance, a Euclidean minimum spanning tree is the same as a graph minimum spanning tree in a complete graph with Euclidean edge weights.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] A spanning tree chosen randomly from among all the spanning trees with equal probability is called a uniform spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Wilson's algorithm can be used to generate uniform spanning trees in polynomial time by a process of taking a random walk on the given graph and erasing the cycles created by this walk.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] An alternative model for generating spanning trees randomly but not uniformly is the random minimal spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In this model, the edges of the graph are assigned random weights and then the minimum spanning tree of the weighted graph is constructed.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Because a graph may have exponentially many spanning trees, it is not possible to list them all in polynomial time.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] However, algorithms are known for listing all spanning trees in polynomial time per tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Every finite connected graph has a spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] However, for infinite connected graphs, the existence of spanning trees is equivalent to the axiom of choice.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] An infinite graph is connected if each pair of its vertices forms the pair of endpoints of a finite path.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] As with finite graphs, a tree is a connected graph with no finite cycles, and a spanning tree can be defined either as a maximal acyclic set of edges or as a tree that contains every vertex.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The trees within a graph may be partially ordered by their subgraph relation, and any infinite chain in this partial order has an upper bound (the union of the trees in the chain).
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Zorn's lemma, one of many equivalent statements to the axiom of choice, requires that a partial order in which all chains are upper bounded have a maximal element; in the partial order on the trees of the graph, this maximal element must be a spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Therefore, if Zorn's lemma is assumed, every infinite connected graph has a spanning tree.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] In the other direction, given a family of sets, it is possible to construct an infinite connected graph such that every spanning tree of the graph corresponds to a choice function of the family of sets.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Therefore, if every infinite connected graph has a spanning tree, then the axiom of choice is true.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] The idea of a spanning tree can be generalized to directed multigraphs.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] Given a vertex *v* on a directed multigraph *G*, an *oriented spanning tree* *T* rooted at *v* is an acyclic subgraph of *G* in which every vertex other than *v* has outdegree 1.
[src:kruskal-mst/spanning-tree] This definition is only satisfied when the "branches" of *T* point towards *v*.
